raw_mentions: Within certain embodiments, substituted 2-cyclohexyl-4-phenyl-1H-imidazole derivatives provided herein exhibit a K<sub>i </sub>of 1 micromolar or less, 100 nanomolar or less, or 10 nanomolar or less in an NPY5 receptor ligand binding assay as provided in Example 11.

A modulator binds “specifically” to NPY5 receptor if it binds human NPY5 receptor (total binding minus nonspecific binding) with a Ki that is 10-fold, preferably 100-fold, and more preferably 1000-fold, less than the Ki measured for modulator binding to other NPY receptors, such as NPY1.
A modulator binds with “high affinity” if the K<sub>i </sub>at an NPY receptor is less than 1 micromolar, preferably less than 100 nanomolar or 10 nanomolar.

Here are the extracted sentences that meet the criteria:


Preferably, such a compound will exhibit a K<sub>i </sub>at an NPY5 receptor of less than 1 micromolar, more preferably less than 500 nM, 100 nM, 20 nM or 10 nM, within an assay performed as described in Example 11.

Here are the extracted sentences that meet the criteria:

* For competition analysis, membranes (5–50 μg) were added to polypropylene tubes containing 0.050 nM [<sup>125</sup>I]PYY(porcine) and 2 μl test compound in DMSO (1 μM–4 μM final concentration).
* Nonspecific binding was determined in the presence of 1 μM NPY (human; American Peptide Co., Sunnyvale, Calif.) and accounted for less than 10% of total binding.
* The binding affinity for the compounds provided herein, expressed as a Ki value, ranged from about 0.1 nanomolar to about 10 micromolar.
* The most active of these compounds have a Ki of less than 100 nanomolar.
* After washing, 80 μl KRH buffer with carbachol/Thomae (KRH buffer containing 1 mM carbachol, 10 micromolar BIBP 3226 (Sigma RBI, St. Louis Mo.)) was added to each well.
